        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.3.23" />

                <fw type="curatorial">23</fw>
                
                                    <fw type="letterhead">
                                        <hi rend="caps">
                                            THE FRANK A. MUNSEY COMPANY
                                                <lb/>
                                                175 FIFTH AVENUE
                                                    <lb/>
                                                    NEW YORK</hi>        
                                        <lb/>

                    Munsey's Magazine
                        <lb/>
                    The Argosy   
                        <lb/>
                    The All-Story Magazine  
                        <lb/>
                    The Railroad &amp; Current Mechanics
                        <lb/>
                    The Cavalier (Issued Weekly)</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 29, 1914.</dateline>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">RHD</hi>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt,</addrLine>

                            <addrLine>Bancroft, Nebraska.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>My dear John:-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>No good poet like yourself can afford to ignore for very long even the freshest of editors like yours truly. George Sterling dropped in on me yesterday and in a glassy-eyed rhapsody talked about your poetic gifts. At the conclusion of his deluge of applause I remarked, somewhat coldly, "Didn't John say anything about me?"</p>

                <p>"I believe not," said Sterling. Whereupon I burst with a loud report and concluded that you had absolutely forgotten me. Drop me a line, old friend, and let me know how the children are coming along, what your hopes are, and tell me why you never send us any more poetry. Let your pen run wild in a letter that you know would interest me. And in reply I will try and communicate some things to you that may be readable.</p>

                <p>The last letter you wrote me was from Minneapolis. That was over a year ago. Surely all this time couldn't have intervened without your doing something important.</p>

                <p>Sterling intends to camp in this town permanently. I pulled out some back numbers of our magazine and showed him some of your best poetry. He has a rather high opinion of you, John - in fact,we both have.</p>

                <p>I don't know what has become of Volney Streamer. I haven't seen him for months. Do you intend ever to show yourself again in New York? Have you given up short stories and novels? It is useless for me to go on asking questions, and I will say nothing further until I hear from you again.</p>

                <p>With my best wishes to Mrs. Neihardt, the last baby, and your firstborn, Enid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Ever sincerely,</salute>
                    
                    <signed><unclear>Robert Davis</unclear></signed>

                    <note>GEJ</note>
                </closer>

            </div1>
